"""
MKT Context Commentary — Revelation chapters 12–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-revelation-12-16.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/revelation.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/revelation.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/revelation.json (ch 12:1 already present)

Key decisions:
- Ch 12 woman: composite figure — Israel (Isa 26:17; 66:7-8), the covenant community,
  not the Virgin Mary exclusively; the twelve stars draw on Gen 37:9 (Joseph's dream)
- Ch 13 beast: deliberately combines Dan 7's four beasts into one; Nero redivivus myth
  (the wounded head healed) is the most plausible first-century historical anchor
- 666 at 13:18: gematria for 'Neron Caesar' in Hebrew consonants (nrwn qsr = 666);
  Greek spelling 'Neron' = 666; Latin 'Nero' = 616 (some mss read 616, supporting this)
- Ch 14 virgins: ritual purity in the tradition of holy-war celibacy (Deut 23:9-10;
  1QM) rather than literal celibacy; the 144,000 are the whole people of God as a
  warrior-community
- Ch 16 bowl plagues: deliberate Exodus typology -- each bowl corresponds to an
  Egyptian plague; the angel of waters hymn echoes the Lex Talionis principle applied
  cosmically; Armageddon = Har-Megiddo (hill of Megiddo), site of Josiah's death and
  Deborah's victory
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

REVELATION = {
  "12": {
    "2": '<p>The laboring woman draws on two Isaianic birth-pangs oracles: Isa 26:17 ("Like a pregnant woman who writhes and cries out in her birth pangs when she is near to giving birth, so were we before you, O LORD") and Isa 66:7-8 (Zion giving birth before her labor begins -- the sudden birth of the eschatological nation). The first-century audience familiar with these texts would recognize the woman as Zion/Israel in eschatological labor. The labor is real and painful -- not merely figurative -- signaling that the birth of the messianic child comes through anguish rather than easy triumph.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The red dragon\'s seven heads and ten horns directly echo Daniel\'s four-beast vision (Dan 7:7-8, 20, 24 -- the fourth beast with ten horns) and the seven-headed Leviathan of Canaanite mythology (the sea-monster Yam/Lotan who opposes the divine order in Ugaritic texts; cf. Ps 74:14; Isa 27:1). John fuses the ANE chaos-monster with Daniel\'s historical empire-beasts into a single comprehensive adversary. The seven crowns (<em>diadēmata</em>) are royal crowns -- counterfeit royalty claiming dominion that belongs to the Lamb. Red (<em>pyrros</em>) evokes fire and blood -- the color of warfare and destruction throughout the ancient world.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The sweeping of a third of the stars echoes Dan 8:10, where the little horn (Antiochus IV Epiphanes) cast some of the host of heaven to the ground -- applied there to the persecution of Israel, recoded here as the dragon\'s primordial violence. In Second Temple apocalyptic, fallen stars represent fallen angels (1 Enoch 86:1-3; 88:1; cf. Rev 9:1). The dragon standing before the woman to devour the child echoes the Herod narrative (Matt 2:13-16) but also the mythological pattern of the sea-dragon threatening the divine birth found across ANE traditions.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The male child "who is to rule all the nations with an iron rod" quotes Ps 2:9 directly -- the royal Psalm of the Davidic king as God\'s vicegerent over the nations. The "iron rod" (<em>rhabdo sidera</em>) represents absolute sovereignty that cannot be resisted (cf. Rev 2:27; 19:15, where the same phrase appears for Christ\'s return). The catching up of the child to God\'s throne compresses the entire paschal event -- incarnation, crucifixion, resurrection, and ascension -- into a single narrative beat, focusing on the end-point: the enthronement that defeats the dragon\'s plan.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The wilderness as the place of divine protection draws directly on Exodus typology: the wilderness was where Israel was sheltered by God (Exod 16:32; Deut 8:2-5; 29:5; Hos 2:14-15). The "1,260 days" (= 42 months = 3.5 years = "time, times, and half a time," 12:14) is the Danielic tribulation period from Dan 7:25 and 12:7 -- exactly half of seven, the number of completion. This half-seven appears across Daniel as the duration of intense but bounded persecution: intense because demonic, bounded because God has set the limit. The "prepared place" echoes Isa 40:3 and signals divine intentionality -- the wilderness period is not random suffering but ordered by God.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The heavenly war draws on the tradition of Michael as Israel\'s angelic patron and champion -- first named at Dan 10:13, 21 as the prince who fights for Israel against Persia\'s heavenly prince, and at Dan 12:1 as the great prince who stands for God\'s people during the final distress. The War Scroll (1QM) from Qumran describes the final eschatological war between the sons of light and sons of darkness, led by Michael on the divine side. The victory here is the heavenly counterpart to Christ\'s death and resurrection on earth.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The dragon losing his place in heaven echoes Luke 10:18 ("I saw Satan fall like lightning from heaven") and the background tradition of the Watchers\' expulsion from heaven (1 Enoch 10:4-8; 14:5; Jude 6; 2 Pet 2:4). The "no longer any place" (<em>oute topos heurethē autōn</em>) is judicial language -- the accuser loses standing. In Second Temple Jewish thought, Satan had access to heaven as the heavenly accuser (Job 1-2; Zech 3:1-2); Christ\'s death removes the legal basis for that accusation, and the expulsion is the heavenly enactment of that legal reality.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The four-name identification of the dragon -- "great dragon," "ancient serpent," "devil," "Satan" -- explicitly connects the Genesis 3 serpent with the cosmic adversary of the NT. "Devil" (<em>diabolos</em>) = the one who throws accusations; "Satan" (Hebrew <em>satan</em>) = the adversary, the accuser (Job 1-2; Zech 3:1). The whole world being "led astray" (<em>planōn tēn oikoumenēn holēn</em>) echoes the prophetic accusation against idolatry as deception and fornication.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The heavenly voice announcing "Now have come the salvation and the power and the kingdom of our God and the authority of his Christ" uses the same royal-accession language as the Psalms of Enthronement (Ps 47; 93; 96-99) and Daniel\'s vision of the Ancient of Days granting the Son of Man dominion (Dan 7:13-14). The title "the accuser of our brothers" (<em>ho katēgōr</em>) is rooted in the Zechariah 3 scene where Satan accuses the high priest Joshua before God, and in the Job 1-2 framework of Satan as the heavenly prosecutor.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The three-part victory formula -- "the blood of the Lamb," "the word of their testimony," "not loving their lives to death" -- defines the shape of Christian conquest in the context of Roman persecution. The "blood of the Lamb" echoes the Passover blood that protected Israel from the destroyer (Exod 12:13, 23). "The word of their testimony" is the public confession that marked martyrs as witnesses (<em>martyres</em>, literally "witnesses"); early Christians who refused to recant under torture were exercising this testimony. "Not loving their lives to death" echoes Pliny\'s description of Christian martyrs in Bithynia (c. 112 CE) who refused to curse Christ under threat of execution.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Woe to the earth and sea" follows the pattern of prophetic woe oracles (Isa 5:8-23; Amos 5:18; 6:1; Hab 2:6-19). The theological logic is precise: the devil\'s great wrath is because he knows his time is short (<em>oligon kairon echei</em>). This same bounded-time awareness appears in the demons who fear being sent away "before the time" (Matt 8:29; Mark 1:24). The fury of the adversary intensifies precisely because his defeat is certain and the hour is near -- the intensification of persecution is a sign of imminent end, not of the enemy\'s strength.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The dragon pursuing the woman restates 12:4-5 from the dragon\'s perspective after his heavenly expulsion -- the pursuit shifts from heavenly to earthly theater. In the first century, this earthly theater would be experienced as Roman imperial persecution of Jewish and Christian communities -- the birth of the messiah sets in motion the empire\'s hostility against the covenant community.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The woman given "the two wings of a great eagle" to fly to the wilderness directly quotes Exod 19:4 ("how I bore you on eagles\' wings and brought you to myself") and Deut 32:10-11 (God finding Israel in the desert waste, spreading his wings over them). The Exodus deliverance was the paradigmatic rescue -- John\'s audience recognized the eagle-wings as the covenant protection that carried Israel through the wilderness. The same image appears in Isa 40:31 (those who wait on the LORD mount up with wings like eagles) -- the wilderness period is not abandoned wandering but sustained divine transport.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The serpent pouring out a river of water after the woman echoes the Exodus typology reversed: Pharaoh drowned Israel\'s sons in the Nile; the dragon attempts to drown the woman in a flood. The "flood" imagery also appears in Ps 32:6 (the rush of great waters), Ps 69:1-2 (waters coming up to the soul), and Isa 59:19 (the enemy coming in like a flood). Persecution as overwhelming water is standard OT imagery for powerful adversarial attack.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The earth opening its mouth and swallowing the river reverses the pattern of Num 16:30-33, where the earth opened its mouth and swallowed the rebellious Korah -- here the earth acts in favor of the woman. The cooperation of creation in the protection of God\'s people is an extension of the covenant order established at creation, paralleling the way the Red Sea protected Israel while drowning the Egyptians (Exod 14:27-28).</p>',
    "17": '<p>The dragon\'s war against "the rest of her offspring -- those who keep the commandments of God and hold to the testimony of Jesus" provides John\'s own definition of the woman\'s seed: the Christian community, defined by covenant obedience and public testimony. "Keep the commandments of God" echoes the Shema-keeping identity of Torah-observant Israel; "hold to the testimony of Jesus" (<em>echontōn tēn martyrian Iēsou</em>) is the specifically Christological confession -- the offspring of the woman belong to both the covenant community and to Christ.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The beast rising from the sea deliberately combines and recapitulates all four of Daniel\'s beasts (Dan 7:2-7) into a single figure: ten horns (Dan 7:7, 24 -- the fourth beast), seven heads (the number of totality), and the features of lion, bear, and leopard drawn from Dan 7:4-6. In Daniel, the four beasts represent successive world empires (Babylon, Persia, Greece, Rome); John\'s synthesis means the final beast embodies all that is worst in every empire. The sea was the origin of chaos and disorder in ANE cosmology (the Ugaritic Yam/Lotan, the Babylonian Tiamat) -- the beast rises from the cosmic source of opposition to divine order.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The dragon giving "his power and his throne and great authority" to the beast establishes the demonic authorization of the empire. In Roman political theology, emperors claimed divine authority -- their <em>auctoritas</em> was absolute and cosmic. John inverts this: the real source behind imperial power is the dragon, not Jupiter. The seven-headed beast of Rome seated on seven hills (17:9) was recognizable to John\'s audience as the city on the Tiber and its empire.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The "mortal wound that was healed" most naturally invokes the Nero redivivus myth -- the widespread belief after Nero\'s suicide (68 CE) that he would return from the east with Parthian armies. Suetonius, Tacitus, and Dio Cassius document this expectation; the Sibylline Oracles (4.138-139; 5.33-35, 137-154) develop the "Nero returning from the dead" tradition in Jewish and early Christian apocalyptic. The healed wound is a counterfeit resurrection -- the beast\'s "return from death" mimics Christ\'s actual resurrection (5:6, the Lamb "as though it had been slaughtered").</p>',
    "4": '<p>The imperial cult -- worship of the emperor as divine -- was a live religious-political phenomenon in Roman Asia Minor in the late first century. Domitian (r. 81-96 CE) demanded to be addressed as <em>dominus et deus</em> (lord and god). Temples to Roma and the emperor existed throughout the province of Asia, including at Ephesus (temple of Domitian), Smyrna, Pergamum, and Sardis. Refusing to worship the imperial image was a political as well as religious act. "Who is like the beast?" (<em>tis homoios tō thēriō</em>) mimics the divine acclamation formula "who is like God?" from Exod 15:11 and Mic 7:18 -- a blasphemous parody.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The "mouth uttering haughty words and blasphemies" and the "forty-two months" of authority both come from Dan 7:8, 25 (the little horn with a mouth speaking great things, given power for "a time, times, and half a time" against the Most High). The forty-two months = 1,260 days = 3.5 years -- the standard Danielic tribulation period. The passive "was given" (<em>edothē</em>) throughout this chapter reflects the divine-passive convention -- God permits rather than causes. The bounded authority is the key contextual note: the beast\'s power is real but temporary and divinely limited.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Blaspheming God\'s name, dwelling, and "those who dwell in heaven" echoes Antiochus IV Epiphanes\' desecration of the Jerusalem temple (167 BCE) -- he erected an altar to Zeus Olympios in the sanctuary (1 Macc 1:54; Dan 11:31; 12:11 -- "the abomination of desolation"). Antiochus\'s blasphemies were the original historical referent for Daniel\'s little-horn prophecy; John applies the same pattern to Rome. Those who "dwell in heaven" are probably the martyred saints and angels (cf. 6:9-11; 7:9-17) whose heavenly status the beast cannot touch despite his earthly power.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Authority "over every tribe and people and language and nation" is the universal sovereignty formula used in Daniel for divine and imperial dominion alike (Dan 3:4; 4:1; 7:14 -- the Son of Man receives authority over "all peoples, nations, and languages"). The beast receives a parody of this universal authority -- real power over the physical world, but not the eternal authority given to the Lamb (5:9; 7:9). The war against the saints and their conquest echoes Dan 7:21 (the little horn making war with the saints and prevailing), where the conquest is temporary -- until the Ancient of Days renders judgment.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The "book of life of the Lamb slaughtered from the foundation of the world" introduces the heavenly-books tradition: in Second Temple Judaism, heavenly books recording the deeds and destinies of the righteous were standard in apocalyptic (Dan 7:10; 1 Enoch 81:1-4; 89:61-70; 4 Ezra 6:20). The grammar allows two readings: names written in the book before creation (cf. Eph 1:4; Rev 17:8) or the Lamb slaughtered in God\'s eternal purpose before creation (cf. 1 Pet 1:20). Both readings are attested in early Christian reflection.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"If anyone has an ear, let him hear" is the identical formula Jesus uses at the end of each of the seven parables (Matt 13:9, 43) and each of the seven letters (Rev 2:7, 11, 17, 29; 3:6, 13, 22) -- the call for discernment in hearing. Its appearance here in the middle of the beast description signals a pause for prophetic reflection rather than simple narrative continuation. The audience is being invited to read the vision as symbolic proclamation requiring interpretation rather than technical futurology.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"If anyone is to go into captivity, into captivity he will go; if anyone is to be killed with the sword, with the sword he will be killed" is a deliberate restatement of Jer 15:2 and Jer 43:11 -- Jeremiah\'s oracle to Jerusalem before the Babylonian exile. The application to John\'s audience is pointed: as Jerusalem faced Babylon, the churches face Rome -- and the calling in both cases is patient endurance and faithfulness rather than violent resistance. The verse rebukes both despair and armed revolt.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The second beast rising from the earth with "two horns like a lamb but speaking like a dragon" is identified later as the "false prophet" (16:13; 19:20; 20:10). The two lamb-horns mimic the Lamb of Rev 5 -- a religious authority that appears religious (lamb = sacrifice/innocence) but is satanically driven. In first-century Asia Minor, the most plausible identification is the provincial priesthood responsible for maintaining the imperial cult -- civic religious officials who organized festivals, sacrifices, and ceremonies honoring the emperor.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The second beast compelling worship of the first beast parallels the role of the provincial <em>koinon</em> (the league of Asian cities) in organizing imperial cult worship. The <em>koinon</em> of Asia appointed priests, built temples, and held games in honor of the emperor -- this was voluntary initially but became compulsory under Domitian. The "mortal wound that was healed" -- the earth-beast causing all to worship the sea-beast in light of this miracle -- echoes how wonder-working prophets established religious authority throughout the ancient world (cf. Deut 13:1-5, the test of the false prophet who performs signs).</p>',
    "13": '<p>Making "fire come down from heaven to earth in front of everyone" mimics the prophetic signs of Elijah (1 Kgs 18:37-38 -- fire from heaven on Carmel; 2 Kgs 1:10-12 -- fire consuming the soldiers). The false prophet\'s fire-sign is a counterfeit of the Elijah-type prophetic credential. In Second Temple Judaism, Elijah was expected to return to authenticate the final prophet (Mal 4:5-6; Sir 48:10) -- signs and wonders were the validating credentials of prophetic authority. Deut 13:1-5 warns that true signs can accompany false prophets who lead Israel astray.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Setting up the "image of the beast" echoes Nebuchadnezzar\'s golden image (Dan 3:1-18) -- the Babylonian tyrant who required universal bow-worship of his statue under penalty of death. The three Hebrew youths who refused are the paradigm of faithful resistance John\'s audience is called to emulate (cf. 13:15\'s penalty for refusal). The image of the emperor (statues, coins, and medallions carrying the emperor\'s image and divine titles) pervaded civic life in Roman Asia -- every major transaction, sacrifice, and civic ceremony involved the emperor\'s image.</p>',
    "15": '<p>An image given "breath" (<em>pneuma</em>) so that it could "speak" echoes the LXX of Ezek 37:5-10 (God breathing life into the dry bones) -- the false prophet mimics the resurrection-life that belongs to God alone. Ancient sources describe speaking-statues as priestly technology used in temple cults (Lucian, <em>Alexander the False Prophet</em>). Whether literal or figurative, the "death sentence" for refusing to worship establishes the context of John\'s letters to the churches: refusal to participate in imperial cult worship was a capital offense.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The mark on "the right hand or the forehead" inverts the Deuteronomic commandment to bind the law "as a sign on your hand and as frontlets between your eyes" (Deut 6:8; 11:18) and the priestly mark of Ezek 9:4 (the <em>taw</em> on the foreheads of those who mourn Jerusalem\'s sin). The beast\'s mark is a counter-covenant mark -- the claim of the beast on the body-politic as opposed to God\'s claim on his covenant people. In Roman commerce, slaves were branded with their owner\'s mark; Roman soldiers might tattoo the name of their commander. The mark is a stamp of ownership and allegiance.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Economic exclusion -- "no one could buy or sell unless he had the mark" -- reflects the way the imperial cult was embedded in commercial life in Roman Asia Minor. The trade guilds (<em>collegia</em>) governing economic life in cities like Corinth and Ephesus typically held regular cultic meals honoring their patron deity and the emperor; refusal to participate put one outside the guild and thus outside legitimate commerce. Pliny\'s letter to Trajan (c. 112 CE) notes that before his crackdown on Christians, meat markets and temples in Bithynia had fallen into disuse -- suggesting Christians were already abstaining from market activities connected to idol worship, with economic consequences.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The number 666 is a classic example of gematria -- the practice of assigning numerical values to letters and summing them, well attested in Pompeii graffiti and throughout the ancient world (e.g., "I love her whose number is 545," CIL 4.5296). The most widely accepted identification: "Neron Caesar" transliterated into Hebrew consonants (<em>nrwn qsr</em>) = 50+200+6+50+100+60+200 = 666. A variant spelling without the final <em>nun</em> (Nero without the terminal "n") = 616, matching the minority textual variant in some manuscripts. The riddle served dual functions: it communicated clearly to insiders while being deniable before hostile authorities.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>The Lamb standing on Mount Zion with the 144,000 fulfills the eschatological gathering promised in Ps 2:6 ("I have set my King on Zion, my holy hill") and Isa 24:23 ("The LORD of hosts reigns on Mount Zion and in Jerusalem"). Zion as the eschatological gathering place appears throughout the prophets (Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-4; Joel 2:32; Zech 8:3). The 144,000 here stand in contrast to those who received the beast\'s mark (13:16-17) -- the same number as the sealed tribes of ch. 7, now seen in their post-tribulation glory. The name on their foreheads is the counter-mark to the beast\'s mark: God\'s ownership inscribed where the beast\'s claim would otherwise be.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The "voice from heaven like the sound of many waters" echoes Ezek 1:24 (the sound of the divine chariot-throne, like the voice of the Almighty) and Ezek 43:2 (the glory of God coming from the east, his voice like the sound of many waters). The harpists\' music adds the temple worship dimension -- harps were the instruments of Levitical psalmody (1 Chr 25:1-7; Ps 33:2; 71:22; 98:5). The heavenly scene combines theophanic (divine presence like the sea and thunder) with liturgical (harps and new song).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A "new song" (<em>oden kainen</em>) marks new acts of divine salvation throughout the Psalms (33:3; 40:3; 96:1; 98:1; 144:9; 149:1) and Isaiah (Isa 42:10) -- the new song in these texts is always eschatological, celebrating salvation breaking in. That only the 144,000 can learn the song connects to the covenant-insider knowledge reserved for those "redeemed from the earth" -- the song belongs to the redeemed by virtue of their redemption, the same logic as the new song of 5:9 (the four creatures and elders singing to the Lamb).</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Who have not defiled themselves with women, for they are virgins" (<em>parthenos</em>) draws on the holy-war purity tradition of Deut 23:9-10 (the warrior must be ceremonially clean when the camp is holy) and 1 Sam 21:5 (David\'s men had kept themselves from women when going on a campaign). The War Scroll (1QM 7:3-6) similarly requires that warriors who fight in the eschatological war must abstain from sexual relations (cf. Num 5:3; Deut 23:9-10). The 144,000 as a spiritual warrior-community following the Lamb: "virgins" denotes ritual purity for holy-war, not a literal celibacy requirement for salvation.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"No lie was found in their mouths; they are blameless" (<em>amomoi</em>) echoes the language of the cultic unblemished sacrifice (Lev 1:3, 10; 3:1, 6 -- the unblemished animal, <em>tamim</em> in Hebrew, <em>amomos</em> in LXX) and the Wisdom tradition of the righteous person whose lips speak truth (Ps 32:2; Isa 53:9 -- "no deceit in his mouth," applied to the Suffering Servant). The combination of no-lie and blameless frames the 144,000 as both the sacrificially-pure and the ethically-pure.</p>',
    "6": '<p>An angel flying "in midheaven" with "an eternal gospel to proclaim to those who dwell on earth, to every nation and tribe and language and people" is the only occurrence of "eternal gospel" in the NT. The universal scope -- "every nation, tribe, language, people" -- echoes the fourfold formula used in 5:9 and 7:9 for the redeemed from every nation, and in 13:7 for the beast\'s universal authority. The angel-proclamation of the gospel may reflect the Jewish expectation of an eschatological proclamation (Isa 52:7; Nah 1:15 -- the messenger announcing peace/good news) universalized to all nations at the end.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Fear God and give him glory, for the hour of his judgment has come" echoes the Danielic "hour of judgment" motif (Dan 7:9-12; 8:17) and the prophetic announcement that the day of the LORD is near (Joel 2:1; Amos 5:18-20; Zeph 1:14). "Worship him who made heaven and earth, the sea and the springs of water" uses the Creator-formula from Exod 20:11 and Neh 9:6 -- the argument that the one who made all things deserves worship over all things. This was standard Jewish apologetic against idolatry in Greco-Roman contexts (Wisdom of Solomon 13-15; Sibylline Oracles 3.8-35).</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great" quotes the LXX of Isa 21:9 verbatim: "She has fallen! Babylon has fallen!" -- the oracle of doom against historical Babylon. The repetition ("Fallen, fallen") is the prophetic perfect -- the future is so certain it is spoken as accomplished. In Jer 51:7, Babylon is described as "a golden cup in the LORD\'s hand, making all the earth drunken" -- the exact metaphor of making nations drunk with the wine of her immorality that Rev 14:8 employs. By Revelation\'s time, "Babylon" had become a Jewish and early Christian codeword for Rome (cf. 1 Pet 5:13; Sibylline Oracles 5.143, 159).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The third angel\'s warning against receiving the mark and worshipping the image follows the first two proclamations (gospel, Babylon fallen) to constitute a complete prophetic message: invitation, announcement, warning. The angel "follows" (<em>akolouthei</em>) the first two -- the three angels form a sequential proclamation to the whole earth. The judicial announcement here -- rather than moral appeal -- reflects the context of the imperial cult: this is about what John\'s audience faces in their concrete civic situation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The "wine of God\'s wrath poured unmixed" combines two OT images: the cup of divine wrath that the nations drink (Ps 75:8; Jer 25:15-16; Isa 51:17, 22; Hab 2:16) and the "unmixed" emphasis. In the ancient world, wine was almost always mixed with water (2-3 parts water to 1 part wine); to serve wine unmixed (<em>akratos</em>) was the mark of a disastrously excessive symposium -- the wrath of God poured at full strength, undiluted. The torment "with fire and sulfur" echoes the destruction of Sodom (Gen 19:24-25; Deut 29:23; Isa 34:9-10; Ezek 38:22) as the paradigmatic case of divine judgment by fire and sulfur.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"The smoke of their torment goes up forever and ever" draws on Isa 34:9-10, the oracle against Edom: "Night and day it shall not be quenched; its smoke shall go up forever." The Isaiah context is the permanent desolation of Edom as representative of all God\'s enemies -- here applied eschatologically to those who worship the beast. "No rest day or night" reverses the Sabbath-rest that belongs to God\'s people (Heb 4:9-11) -- the unrepentant find no rest in the age to come.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Here is a call for the patient endurance of the saints" (<em>hode he hypomone ton hagion estin</em>) is the same formula as 13:10, forming a deliberate bracket around the beast-judgment section. <em>Hypomone</em> (patient endurance) is the characteristic virtue commended to all seven churches (2:2, 3, 19; 3:10; cf. Rom 5:3-4; Jas 1:3-4). The saints are defined as those who "keep the commandments of God and their faith in Jesus" -- the dual covenant identity (Torah + Christological confession) that characterized Jewish Christianity. The immediate social context: the economic and civic pressures of the imperial cult system required precisely this patient endurance rather than violent revolt or quiet accommodation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Blessed are the dead who die in the Lord from now on" is the second of the seven beatitudes in Revelation (cf. 1:3; 16:15; 19:9; 20:6; 22:7, 14). The Spirit\'s affirmation "Yes" echoes the divine confirming voice at Jesus\'s baptism and transfiguration. The promise that their deeds "follow" (<em>akolouthei</em>) them after death reverses the normal trajectory -- in Greco-Roman thought and popular Jewish belief, the dead left their deeds behind; here the deeds accompany the dead into the blessed state. The immediate context of Roman martyrdom makes this pastoral affirmation urgent: dying under imperial persecution is not loss but entry into rest.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The one "like a son of man with a golden crown seated on a white cloud" with a "sharp sickle" draws directly on Dan 7:13 (one like a son of man coming with the clouds of heaven) and Joel 3:13 ("Put in the sickle, for the harvest is ripe; go in, tread, for the winepress is full"). The golden wreath-crown (<em>stephanos</em>, not the royal diadem <em>diadema</em>) and the white cloud belong to the imagery of divine theophany (Ps 104:3; Isa 19:1; Dan 7:13) and victorious procession.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The angel "coming out of the temple" calling for the harvest reflects the angelic mediation of divine commands found throughout Revelation (8:2-5; 9:1-2; etc.) and in the broader apocalyptic tradition (1 Enoch 60; 4 Ezra 4-5). The harvest command directly quotes Joel 3:13a: "Put in your sickle and reap, for the harvest is fully ripe." In Joel\'s context, the harvest is the judgment of the nations gathered in the Valley of Jehoshaphat -- a judgment harvest universalized here to the whole earth.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The earth being "reaped" parallels the harvest imagery of the parable of the wheat and weeds (Matt 13:36-43, where the harvest is the end of the age and the reapers are angels), and the grain harvest of Jer 51:33 (the daughter of Babylon has reached harvest time). The two harvests in vv. 14-20 (grain and grape) may represent two groups -- the redeemed gathered first, the condemned pressed in wrath -- following the pattern of Matt 13:30 (gather the wheat first, then the weeds for burning).</p>',
    "17": '<p>A second angel with a sharp sickle coming from the heavenly temple initiates a second harvest distinct from the first. The heavenly temple as the source of judgment angels appears repeatedly in Revelation (8:3-5; 11:19; 15:5-6; 16:1, 17) -- the presence of God in his sanctuary is the source of both redemption and judgment. The two harvests (grain and grape) correspond to the pattern of Matt 13:30 and the OT distinction between gathering the righteous and treading the wicked.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The angel "who has authority over fire" echoes the angelology of Second Temple Judaism, which assigned specific angels authority over specific elements and forces of nature (1 Enoch 60:14-22 names angels over wind, fire, hail, frost, mist; Jubilees 2:2 describes the angels of fire and other natural phenomena). The association of this angel with the altar, from which the prayers of the saints rise (8:3-5), ties the grape-harvest judgment to the vindication of the martyrs -- it is in answer to their prayers that the judgment-harvest proceeds.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The "great winepress of the wrath of God" draws on Isa 63:1-6 -- the oracle of the divine warrior returning from Edom with garments stained from the winepress: "I have trodden the winepress alone... I trod them in my anger and trampled them in my wrath; their lifeblood spattered on my garments." Lamentations 1:15 applies the winepress image to Jerusalem under judgment: "The Lord has trodden as in a winepress the virgin daughter of Judah." Joel 3:13 (the winepress is full) is the proximate source. The grape harvest "outside the city" echoes the Levitical requirement that the sin-offering be burned outside the camp (Lev 4:12, 21).</p>',
    "20": '<p>Blood flowing "as high as a horse\'s bridle for 1,600 stadia" (about 184 miles -- roughly the length of ancient Palestine) is hyperbolic apocalyptic imagery; the figure appears in 1 Enoch 100:3 (the horse wading in the blood of sinners up to its chest) and the Sibylline Oracles 2.176-177. The "outside the city" framing draws the circle: the eschatological battle takes place outside Jerusalem/the New Jerusalem, in the space where the winepress operates. The sheer scale (1,600 stadia) signals totality -- complete and universal judgment.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>The "seven angels with the seven last plagues" and the statement that "with them God\'s wrath is completed" (<em>etelesthe ho thymos tou theou</em>) positions ch. 15-16 as the climax and completion of the divine judgment sequence. The word <em>teleo</em> (complete, finish) is the same root as "It is finished" (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30) -- the completion of wrath corresponds to the completion of redemption. The seven plagues as "the last" signals that the bowl sequence outranks the seals and trumpets in finality.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The "sea of glass mixed with fire" develops the sea-of-glass image from Rev 4:6 (the crystalline expanse before the heavenly throne, which itself echoes Exod 24:10 -- the pavement of sapphire under God\'s feet -- and Ezek 1:22 -- the firmament like crystal over the living creatures). The fire mixed with the glass indicates that this heavenly sea is now charged with judgment (fire = divine judgment throughout Revelation; 8:5, 7, 8; 9:17-18). Those standing victorious beside the sea have passed through the fiery trial of persecution without being consumed.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Singing "the song of Moses the servant of God and the song of the Lamb" explicitly identifies the redeemed\'s position with the Israelites at the Red Sea (Exod 15:1-18 -- the Song of Moses after the Exodus). The content echoes Ps 111:2 ("Great are the works of the LORD"), Jer 10:7 ("Who would not fear you, O King of the nations?"), Ps 86:9 ("All the nations you have made shall come and worship before you"), Deut 32:4 ("The Rock, his work is perfect"). The Exodus was the paradigmatic salvation event; the final redemption fulfills and surpasses it. The "servant of God" title echoes Num 12:7, Deut 34:5, Josh 1:2 -- Moses the covenant mediator as the type of the ultimate Mediator.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Who will not fear you, O Lord, and glorify your name? For you alone are holy (<em>hosios</em>), and all nations will come and worship before you, for your righteous acts have been revealed." The question "who will not fear?" echoes Jer 10:7 and Ps 86:9, and the universal worship of all nations fulfills the eschatological vision of Isa 2:2-4 (all nations streaming to Zion), Isa 45:23 (every knee bowing), and Ps 22:27-29 (all ends of the earth turning to the LORD). The term <em>hosios</em> for God -- unusual where <em>hagios</em> is more common -- may echo Ps 145:17 LXX or Deut 32:4 (the God of faithfulness).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The "temple of the tabernacle of the testimony in heaven" (<em>ho naos tes skenes tou martyriou</em>) specifically invokes the wilderness tabernacle -- "tabernacle of testimony" is the phrase used for the portable sanctuary in Exod 38:21, Num 1:50, 53; 9:15; 17:7-8; Acts 7:44. The tabernacle contained the ark of the testimony (ark of the covenant with the stone tablets), hence "testimony" = the tablets/covenant. The opening of the heavenly temple to release the judgment-angels echoes 11:19 (the heavenly temple opened, revealing the ark). The heavenly sanctuary is the reality of which the earthly tabernacle was the copy (Heb 8:5; 9:11, 23-24).</p>',
    "6": '<p>The seven angels come out "clothed in pure, bright linen, with golden sashes around their chests" -- the priestly vestments of Exod 28 (linen garments for the priests) and the description of the heavenly figure in Ezek 9:2-3 (a man clothed in linen with a writing case) and Dan 10:5 (the man clothed in linen with a belt of Uph gold). Linen symbolizes purity (the priestly material, Exod 28:5-8; Lev 16:4, 23) and heavenly status. The golden sashes echo the golden belt of the enthroned figure in Rev 1:13 (the one like a son of man) -- the judgment-angels share the vestment-character of the glorified Christ.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The "seven golden bowls filled with the wrath of God who lives forever and ever" echoes the golden temple vessels of the Jerusalem sanctuary (Exod 25:29-30; Num 4:7; 1 Kgs 7:48-50) -- the holy vessels now filled with divine wrath rather than incense of worship. The golden bowls in 5:8 held "the prayers of the saints" as incense; now they hold the wrath that is the answered prayer of 6:10 ("How long, O Lord?"). The divine title "who lives forever and ever" (<em>to zonti eis tous aionas ton aionon</em>) is the doxological formula from Dan 4:34; 12:7 -- the eternal God whose wrath, like his life, is ultimate and inexhaustible.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The temple filled with smoke "from the glory of God and from his power" so that "no one could enter the temple until the seven plagues were completed" echoes two OT theophanic scenes: (1) the inauguration of the tabernacle (Exod 40:34-35) and temple (1 Kgs 8:10-11), when the glory cloud filled the sanctuary so that even Moses/the priests could not enter; (2) Isaiah\'s throne vision (Isa 6:4), where the temple fills with smoke. The exclusion of entry until judgment is complete mirrors the Day of Atonement restriction (Lev 16:17 -- no one in the tabernacle while the high priest made atonement) -- the cosmic Day of Atonement must run its course before the temple of divine presence is accessible again.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>The "loud voice from the temple" commanding the seven angels to pour out the bowls echoes the command-voice structure of Exod 25-40 (God commanding Moses from the tabernacle) and the divine-command pattern of Ezek 9-10 (the divine voice commanding the judgment of Jerusalem). The bowls follow the pattern of the Exodus plagues (Exod 7-12) in a deliberate new-Exodus typology: the plagues on Egypt that forced Pharaoh\'s hand become the cosmic plagues on the new-Pharaoh (the beast) that precede the final deliverance. The whole creation now experiences the Exodus judgment that Egypt experienced -- with Rome as the new Egypt.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The first bowl -- "ugly, festering sores" on those who had the mark of the beast -- directly parallels the sixth plague on Egypt: "boils breaking out in sores on humans and animals throughout all the land of Egypt" (Exod 9:9-11). The parallel is exact in both the affliction and the selective targeting (those not in covenant with God are afflicted; Israel was protected in Goshen from several plagues). The Deuteronomic covenant curses add another layer: "The LORD will afflict you with... boils and with scurvy and with itch... and you cannot be healed" (Deut 28:27, 35) -- the bowl-plagues are the enacted Deuteronomic curses on a world that has chosen the beast over God.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The second bowl turning the sea to "blood like that of a dead person" -- killing every living creature -- parallels the first Egyptian plague (Exod 7:14-25 -- the Nile turned to blood, killing the fish and making the water undrinkable). The Revelation version is more total than the Exodus plague: all the sea\'s creatures die rather than just those in the Nile. The "blood like that of a dead person" (<em>hos nekrou</em>) -- coagulated, putrefied blood -- intensifies the horror beyond simple blood coloring; it is the blood of corpses, signaling that the sea is already a place of death.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The third bowl affecting rivers and springs parallels both the first Egyptian plague (the Nile, expanded here to all fresh water) and the third trumpet (8:10-11 -- a star poisoning the rivers and springs). The Lex Talionis logic is explicit in vv. 5-6: those who shed the blood of the saints receive blood to drink -- the punishment fits the crime in the most literal way. In ANE covenant curse formulas, the reversal of one\'s deeds upon oneself was standard judicial theology (Ps 9:15-16; Obad 15; Jer 50:15, 29).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The "angel of the waters" hymning God\'s justice introduces the angelology of elemental governance -- specific angels responsible for specific domains of creation, who themselves vindicate the justice of divine judgment. This tradition appears in 1 Enoch 69:22 (the angel of water), Jubilees 2:2 (angels over water), and the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QH 1:10-11). The angel\'s declaration "You are just (<em>dikaios</em>) in these judgments, you who are and who were, the Holy One" is a doxology in the face of divine judgment -- not grudging admission but worship through acknowledgment of God\'s judicial righteousness.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"For they poured out the blood of your saints and prophets, and you have given them blood to drink -- they deserve it" is the Lex Talionis applied at cosmic scale, echoing Isaiah\'s taunt against Babylon (Isa 49:26 -- "I will make your oppressors eat their own flesh, and they shall be drunk with their own blood as with wine") and Jer 51:35-36 (Babylon\'s violence against Jerusalem returned on her head). The martyrs\' blood (6:9-11; 17:6; 18:24) is the cause; the blood-to-drink is the consequence. The formula "they deserve it" (<em>axioi eisin</em>) is standard in judicial pronouncements in apocalyptic -- the sentence fits the crime.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The altar "responding" with a doxology -- "Yes, Lord God Almighty, your judgments are true and just" -- anthropomorphizes the altar as the locus of the martyrs\' prayers (6:9-11; 8:3-5) and the incense of intercession. The altar becomes the voice of answered prayer: the judgment is the answer to the cry "How long?" (6:10). The title "Lord God Almighty" (<em>Kyrie ho theos ho pantokrator</em>) is the LXX rendering of "LORD God of Hosts" -- the divine sovereign whose power is universal and whose judgments cannot be resisted.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The fourth bowl against the sun -- scorching people with fire -- echoes the prophetic imagery of Amos 8:9 ("I will make the sun go down at noon, and darken the earth in broad daylight") and Isa 30:26 (the sun becoming seven times brighter as eschatological light -- here reversed, the sun becomes judgment rather than blessing). The sun, which in the original creation order was given to "govern the day" (Gen 1:16), now scorches rather than sustains -- creation itself becomes the instrument of judgment against those who rejected the Creator.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The response of the victims -- "they blasphemed the name of God who had authority over these plagues and did not repent and give him glory" -- echoes the hardening of Pharaoh\'s heart (Exod 7:13, 22; 8:15, 19, 32; 9:7, 12, 34-35; 10:1, 20, 27; 11:10). Like Pharaoh, those who receive the plagues do not repent but harden in blasphemy. The refusal to repent (<em>metanoia</em>) is the defining mark of those who align with the beast -- they know the source of the plagues and actively blaspheme rather than turn. This is the NT application of Exod 9:16 (Pharaoh as the paradigm of the one who hardens himself against God\'s signs).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The fifth bowl poured on "the throne of the beast" -- plunging its kingdom into darkness -- parallels the ninth Egyptian plague (darkness over all Egypt for three days, Exod 10:21-23 -- "no one could see anyone else... but all the Israelites had light where they lived"). The beast\'s "throne" as the target signals that the center of the rival kingdom -- its political power-base -- is the specific locus of judgment. The darkness on the beast\'s kingdom is the deliberate inversion of the eschatological light promised to God\'s people (22:5 -- the Lord God is their light).</p>',
    "11": '<p>The second refusal to repent in the bowl sequence intensifies: "they cursed the God of heaven because of their pain and their sores." The "God of heaven" (<em>ton theon tou ouranou</em>) is a title used predominantly in Persian-period texts (Ezra 1:2; 6:9-10; 7:12; Neh 1:4; Dan 2:18-19, 37, 44) -- it acknowledges God\'s sovereign heavenly position while maintaining distance. The cursing of this God represents the final stage of the Pharaoh-pattern: recognizing the source of the plagues without any movement toward submission. The "sores" from the first bowl (v. 2) persist -- the plagues accumulate rather than pass.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The sixth bowl drying up the Euphrates River echoes God\'s drying up of the Red Sea for Israel\'s Exodus (Exod 14:21-22; Ps 106:9) and the Jordan (Josh 3:14-17), and Isa 11:15-16 (God drying the river to make a highway for the return of Israel from Assyria). Most specifically, it recalls the fall of Babylon to Cyrus (539 BCE): Herodotus and Xenophon report that Cyrus diverted the Euphrates to gain access to Babylon under its walls through the dry riverbed. The "kings from the east" evokes Cyrus (the king from the east who conquered Babylon) and the feared Parthian cavalry from beyond the Euphrates -- already a standing anxiety in Roman strategic planning throughout the first century.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The "three impure spirits like frogs" from the mouths of the unholy trinity (dragon, beast, false prophet) echoes the second Egyptian plague (frogs from the Nile covering all Egypt, Exod 8:1-15) and the demonic-spirit tradition of Second Temple Judaism (1 Enoch 19:1; Testament of Solomon 1-10). The frog-spirits as "demonic spirits performing signs" to gather kings recall the lying spirit that deceived the prophets of Israel into urging Ahab toward his death (1 Kgs 22:19-23) -- a heavenly-court scene in which God permits a deceptive spirit to operate, resulting in the death of the wicked king.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Demonic spirits performing signs, going out to the kings of the whole world to assemble them for the battle on the great day of God the Almighty" frames the gathering of the nations as a divinely-permitted demonic operation. The "great day of God the Almighty" echoes Joel 2:11 ("the day of the LORD is great and very awesome") and Zeph 1:14-15 ("The great day of the LORD is near"). The nations assemble thinking they are preparing an offensive; they are actually being gathered for judgment -- the same pattern as Ezek 38-39 (Gog and Magog assembled from all nations against Israel, only to be destroyed by God\'s direct intervention).</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Look, I come like a thief" -- the parenthetical warning in 16:15 -- interrupts the narrative of demonic gathering with a pastoral word addressed directly to the churches. The "thief in the night" metaphor appears in Matt 24:43-44 (par. Luke 12:39-40), 1 Thess 5:2-4, and 2 Pet 3:10 -- the Lord\'s coming as unexpected, requiring constant readiness. "Blessed is the one who stays awake and keeps his clothes" echoes the exhortation to the Laodiceans (3:18 -- buy white garments) and the general call to watchfulness (Matt 25:1-13). The nakedness-shame connection (3:18; 16:15) draws on the Genesis 3 pattern: post-Fall nakedness as shame is the condition of those not clothed in Christ\'s righteousness.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Armageddon (<em>Har Megiddon</em>, "Mountain of Megiddo") is the only occurrence of this name in the Bible. Megiddo was a strategic fortress city controlling the Jezreel Valley -- the geographic corridor connecting Egypt and Mesopotamia -- and was the site of decisive ancient battles: Deborah and Barak\'s victory over Sisera (Judg 4-5) and Josiah\'s death in 609 BCE (2 Kgs 23:29-30; cf. Zech 12:11 -- "the mourning at Megiddo"). The "mountain" (<em>har</em>) of Megiddo is puzzling since Megiddo is in a valley; it may reference the adjacent Carmel range or represent the ideal symbolic battle-site. In any case, Megiddo had become a byword for decisive, world-determining battle -- the name is symbolic of the eschatological conflict.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The seventh bowl poured "into the air" -- with the accompanying voice from the throne saying "It is done!" (<em>gegonen</em>) -- echoes Jesus\'s final word from the cross (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30) and God\'s declaration in 21:6 (<em>gegona</em>, "it is done"). The air as the domain of "the prince of the power of the air" (Eph 2:2 -- the Satan figure in Pauline thought) makes the seventh bowl a direct assault on Satan\'s domain. "It is done!" signals the completion of divine judgment. The theophanic response (lightning, thunder, earthquake) echoes the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16-19; 20:18-21) -- God\'s direct self-revelation through natural convulsions.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The "severe earthquake -- no earthquake like it has ever occurred since mankind has been on earth" echoes the standard apocalyptic formula for the eschatological earthquake: Dan 12:1 ("a time of distress such as has not happened from the beginning of nations"), Matt 24:21 (great tribulation such as has not been from the beginning), and Ezek 38:19-20 (the earthquake of Gog\'s defeat that shakes the whole earth). The earthquake as divine judgment theophany pervades the OT (Isa 29:6; Amos 1:1; Zech 14:5; Ps 18:7-8). The unprecedented scale signals the finality of this judgment -- it cannot be followed by another because it is complete.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The "great city split into three parts" likely refers to Babylon/Rome (cf. chs. 17-18). The collapse of "the cities of the nations" signals the cosmic extent of this final judgment -- it is not one city but the whole network of human city-civilization built on the beast\'s authority. "God remembered great Babylon" -- the phrase "God remembered" is the covenantal memory language used of God\'s faithfulness to Noah (Gen 8:1), Abraham (Gen 19:29), Rachel (Gen 30:22), and Hannah (1 Sam 1:19); here it is memory that brings judgment rather than rescue.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Every island fled away and the mountains could no longer be found" echoes the cosmic de-creation of 6:12-14 (the sixth seal -- islands moved, mountains removed) and parallels Isa 40:4 (mountains made low), Jer 4:24 (the mountains quaking), and Nah 1:5 (mountains quaking, hills melting). In the ancient world, islands and mountains were the most stable, immovable features of the earth -- their disappearance signals the total restructuring of the cosmic order. This is not geological destruction but theological: the stable things of the old world-order are dissolved in preparation for the new creation (21:1 -- "the first earth had passed away").</p>',
    "21": '<p>Hailstones "each weighing about a hundred pounds" echoes the seventh Egyptian plague (Exod 9:18-26 -- "hail and fire flashing continually in the midst of the hail, very heavy hail such as had never been in all the land of Egypt"). The measurement (about 100 pounds -- Greek <em>talantiaion</em>, a talent weight) signals total destructive force -- not hailstones that bruise but boulders that kill. The victims\' response -- "they cursed God on account of the plague of hail" -- is the third and final refusal-to-repent in the bowl sequence, completing the Pharaoh-hardening pattern. The pattern of plague-curse-no-repentance is now complete.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(existing, REVELATION)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation', existing)
    print('Revelation 12-16 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
